title: For Sale/Trade:  Dreyse Model 1907 - 32 ACP w/ Holster
postcontent:
This 100+ year old semi-automatic pistol still looks and functions great. Comes with original Lambskin Holster (not the later paper holsters), with one magazine. Test fired and cleaned, all works great.


The Dreyse Model 1907 is a semi-automatic pistol designed by Louis Schmeisser. The gun was named after Nikolaus von Dreyse, the designer of the Dreyse Needle Gun. The Waffenfabrik von Dreyse company was acquired by Rheinische Metallwaren & Maschinenfabrik Sömmerda in 1901, although the Dreyse Model pistols were marketed under the Dreyse name.
The pistol had an interesting feature for the time: when the gun was ready to fire, the firing pin projected through the back of the breech block, serving as an early handgun-cocking indicator. For cleaning, the frame, receiver and slide pivoted forward on a pin in front of the trigger guard. The pistol and its derivatives (Dreyse Model 1907 Pocket Pistol, Dreyse Model 1912 Parabellum) was of simple blowback recoil operation, though of unusual design.[2]

Primarily used by Austrian troops during World War I, especially officers of the Austro-Hungarian Habsburg Empire. Also used by officers of Imperial Germany during World War I.
Examples issued to the Imperial German Army will have an acceptance proof above the ejection port on the right as well as the normal Crown N commercial proofs on the left side of the frame and slide near the trigger.
Examples saw use by Wehrmacht troops (especially officers) during World War II. Nearing the end of the war many examples were issued to the Volksgrenadiere and Volkssturm, the latter often with so-called "last-ditch" Presstoff holsters. Large numbers of these were brought back to the United States by returning servicemen, which accounts for their availability in the country today. Typically the paper Presstoff holsters have not survived.
A few thousand were purchased by the Czech military in 1921 and 1922, but they were removed from service in 1923 due to unspecified accidents with them.
In 1912 the pope's Swiss Guard acquired thirty of these pistols for use by officers and non-commissioned officers. They remained in service until 1990 when they were replaced by the SIG P225 pistol as the P75.[4]
During World War II this pistol found its way to the Norwegian resistance. Quite a few of these pistols have, alongside home-made Sten-guns and illegal radios, been found hidden within the house-walls of Norwegian resistance members and sympathisers.

title: For Sale:  1929 Colt Official Police - 38 sp. - 6in Barrel - Reduced
postcontent:
COLT OFFICIAL POLICE: Used, 38 Spl, 6 inch barrel, double action. This shows 80 year old duty use and wear. Action is great and functions like a Colt should. Blue is worn in areas and a nice patina shows. The grips are pre-war walnut, but have a decent chip out of them just behind the trigger guard.


Introduced to the firearms market in 1927, The Colt Official Police is a medium frame, six-shot, double-action revolver with a six round cylinder, primarily chambered for the .38 Special cartridge, and manufactured by the Colt's Manufacturing Company. The intended specific target market for the Official Police was mainly law enforcement agencies and it became one of the best selling police firearms of all time, eventually in the 1950s coming to exemplify typical peace officer weaponry. The Official Police was also used by various U.S. and allied military forces during World War II.

The Official Police was machined of fine carbon steel, with bright royal Colt blued as well as nickel plated finishes, and was offered in 4”, 5”, and 6” barrels. Built on Colt’s .41 or “I” frame, it was manufactured in a variety of chamberings including .22 LR, .32-20 (discontinued in 1942), .41 Long Colt (discontinued in 1938), and the most common and popular, the .38 Special. Colt’s “Positive Lock” firing pin block safety was a standard feature of the revolver, preventing the firing pin from striking the primer unless the trigger was deliberately pulled. The pistol’s sights consisted of a blade front with a fixed iron open rear sight, which was a simple V-notch shaped groove milled into the revolver’s top strap. The top strap had a matte finish to reduce glare down the sight plane.

title: For Sale:  1929 COLT OFFICIAL POLICE - 38 SP. - 6IN BARREL
postcontent:
COLT OFFICIAL POLICE: Used, 38 Spl, 6 inch barrel, double action. This shows 80 year old duty use and wear. Action is great and functions like a Colt should. Blue is worn in areas and a nice patina shows. The grips are pre-war walnut, but have a decent chip out of them just behind the trigger guard.


Introduced to the firearms market in 1927, The Colt Official Police is a medium frame, six-shot, double-action revolver with a six round cylinder, primarily chambered for the .38 Special cartridge, and manufactured by the Colt's Manufacturing Company. The intended specific target market for the Official Police was mainly law enforcement agencies and it became one of the best selling police firearms of all time, eventually in the 1950s coming to exemplify typical peace officer weaponry. The Official Police was also used by various U.S. and allied military forces during World War II.

The Official Police was machined of fine carbon steel, with bright royal Colt blued as well as nickel plated finishes, and was offered in 4”, 5”, and 6” barrels. Built on Colt’s .41 or “I” frame, it was manufactured in a variety of chamberings including .22 LR, .32-20 (discontinued in 1942), .41 Long Colt (discontinued in 1938), and the most common and popular, the .38 Special. Colt’s “Positive Lock” firing pin block safety was a standard feature of the revolver, preventing the firing pin from striking the primer unless the trigger was deliberately pulled. The pistol’s sights consisted of a blade front with a fixed iron open rear sight, which was a simple V-notch shaped groove milled into the revolver’s top strap. The top strap had a matte finish to reduce glare down the sight plane.

title: For Sale:  Beware Ads For High Capacity Magazines
postcontent:
I've seen a number of ads lately illegally selling high cap magazines. Remember folks, it's no longer legal in Colorado to buy, sell, or trade magazines with capacities over 15 rounds.

It's possible the people placing these ads have been living in caves and are completely clueless about the new magazine law. 

It's also possible the ads are being placed by law enforcement looking to make examples of a few buyers who disregard the new law, or by newspaper/TV reporters wanting to do a story on how this law should be better enforced. 

So just be careful. Don't be the dupe who gets suckered in by cops or reporters.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Upgraded Glock 27 Gen. 4 PLEASE READ DESCRIPTION BEFORE OFFERING ANYTHING!!!
postcontent: I have a Gen.4 Glock 27 that has over $1,500.00 of gunsmith work and upgrades done to it. PLEASE READ FULL DESCRIPTION BEFORE OFFERING ANYTHING. This gun is the ultimate concealed carry edc gun. I will start with the small upgrades and work my way up to the bigger upgrades. I have installed +1 Pearce Grip Extensions on all 3 mags for $15.00. I installed a stainless 6lb. Trigger spring, a 4 lb. striker spring, and a reduced power safety plunger spring for $20.00. I installed a Ghost Evo 3.5 lb. connector for $25.00, and a polished titanium safety plunger for $20.00. It has an aluminum back plate cover. It has polished skeletonized stainless steel striker for $70.00. It has a tungsten recoil assembly for $70.00. I put Trijicon night sights on it installed for $100.00. It has a match grade KKM Precision barrel that was match fitted for $225.00 with the labor. It has a black on black Zev Tech Fulcrum trigger with polished trigger bar and ejector housing that was $180.00. And I've installed a Vickers Tactical Tango Down mag release and slide catch for $40.00.  I didn't just buy all these parts and throw them on the gun either. The frame has been sent off to be centered and made perfectly even. The barrel, trigger assembly, and guide rod have been tuned to have perfect harmonics. It has been set up for a self defense carry gun with a 3.5 lb. trigger pull, but can be adjusted from 6lb. to 2lb. Trigger pull. You can also adjust the pre-travel and after travel of the trigger, and the trigger reset has been reduced by 50% from the factory setting. It is a very smooth crisp Trigger that breaks very clean. I also have a lot of parts that go with it. I have a Zev Tech V4 race connector, and a Lightning Strike titanium polished safety plunger with spring. Also have 3 5lb. Striker springs and 1 6lb. Striker spring. I have another 6lb. Trigger spring, and all the factory parts that were removed. Factory barrel, factory trigger, factory safety plunger, factory striker, and factory sights. I also have a front sight removal tool, and an I-Tac kydex paddle holster with the button release that was $50.00.  I have the case and all paperwork with the back straps, and factory mag base plates. You won't find a better Glock than this. It has been fine tuned to be a perfect everyday carry self defense gun. I can send more pics upon request if you want to see anything in particular. I know what this gun is worth, and I know what I've got in it. If you want a factory glock this isn't for you. I'm not going to trade or sale it for the price of a factory glock. The parts in this gun are worth more than a factory glock. If you are interested then please make a reasonable offer based on what this gun is worth now. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  COLT - ACE Pre-War .22 LR 1911 -- 1st Year Pistol....SN 295....Mfd 1931, C&R OK 1450
postcontent: Here's a Pre-WWII Colt "Ace" semi-automatic pistol. Designed with the intent of being a rimfire companion piece to the famous 1911, this pistol chambers .22LR and operates by simple blow-back. Unlike the later "Service Model Ace", this pistol does not feature a floating chamber and instead has a specially lightened slide, reduced power recoil spring, special recoil spring guide with leather buffers, and a special firing pin retainer with roller bearing. This pistol is all original. The low 3-digit serial number (295) places her in 1931 production, the very first year of manufacture. The serial number is properly matching beneath the firing pin retainer on the slide. Overall condition is very good with handling marks, general finish wear, and thinning at the muzzle and grip straps. There is a small area of pitting on the left side of the slide. I'd grade the original factory blue finish at about 80% overall. The original full checkered walnut grips show some wear but no cracks or chips. The two-tone magazine is also correct/original and in very good shape. The mechanics appear to be in perfect working order and the bore is excellent with bright, sharp rifling. With a production totaling less than 11,000 guns, the Ace is one of the less commonly encountered Colt automatic pistols.
